Bubble Sort
Bubble Sort is one of the simplest sorting algorithms. It works by repeatedly stepping through the list, comparing adjacent elements, and swapping them if they are in the wrong order. The pass through the list is repeated until the list is sorted.

How it works:

Look at the first two elements. If the first is bigger than the second, swap them.

Move to the next pair (the 2nd and 3rd elements) and do the same.

Continue this until you reach the end of the array. At this point, the largest element will have "bubbled up" to the very last position.

Repeat the process for the remaining elements (ignoring the last one, which is already sorted).

Complexity:

Time Complexity: O(n^2) - This means if you double the number of elements, the time taken increases roughly four times. It is slow for large lists.

Space Complexity: O(1) - It sorts the array in place, so it uses very little extra memory.